## Collisions

### You are given two GameObjects (GameObjectCube, GameObjectTerrain). GameObjectCube should fall towards GameObjectTerrain and stop once the GameObjectCube touches GameObjectTerrain. How can this behaviour be achieved?

The straightforward option is to move the cube downward at a fixed speed and stop it when a collision with the terrain is detected.

A simple Unity style approach is to use a `Rigidbody` with `useGravity = false`, assign a constant downward velocity, and zero it on contact.

```csharp
private void Awake()
{
    rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
    rb.useGravity = false;
}

private void Start()
{
    rb.linearVelocity = Vector3.down * fallSpeed;
}

private void OnCollisionEnter(Collision collision)
{
    if (!collision.gameObject.CompareTag("Terrain")) return;

    rb.linearVelocity = Vector3.zero;
}
```

Additional setup may be required to account for damping on velocity, or we can on `FixedUpdate` force the velocity we want each time, although that can present as  hacky and going against the intended system.

For larger numbers of objects, it's worth considering moving away from rigidbodies and using batched queries. RaycastCommand could help identify the terrain point for each falling object and help regularly update or interpolate objects to target point.

---

### GameObjectCube should now reverse the direction (â€œbounce offâ€) of the GameObjectTerrain once they touch and continue travelling in the opposite direction. How would you adjust your previous solution?

Keep the same constant speed but flip the travel direction when contact occurs.

```csharp
private Vector3 direction = Vector3.down;

private void Awake()
{
    rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
    rb.useGravity = false;
    rb.linearDamping = 0f;
}

private void FixedUpdate()
{   // per physics tick reset of values
    rb.linearVelocity = direction * speed;
}

private void OnCollisionEnter(Collision collision)
{
    if (!collision.gameObject.CompareTag("Terrain")) return;
    direction = -direction;
}
```

At scale, if the motion is this simple and deterministic, we can go with data driven movement plus batched collision queries over full per object physics simulation.

If many objects need richer physical interaction rather than simple ping pong motion, that is where a fuller ECS physics approach starts becoming more relevant.

